        "text": "> E. MORIN writes: \"SCHRODINGER, in \"What is Life?\" stated that ordered events could be produced out of two basic principles, the first one \"[[Order from Order]]\" (algorithmic), the second \"order from disorder\" (statistical), from which two types of laws are derived, dynamic laws and statistical ones. Von FOERSTER, in 1959, advanced a third principle, which cannot be confused with the first ones, even if it depends on them: \"Order from noise\" (von FOERSTER 1960, p.31-50). It is a selective principle, according to which noise-events contribute to increase order in complex systems…"
